      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver vendor-supplied benchmark suite executed with all cases passing; version control and audit trail documented.",
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent 2022R2 was used under institutional license with version-controlled case files. Vendor benchmark suite (lid-driven cavity Re=1000, developing pipe flow) executed prior to production runs; all benchmark residuals met convergence criteria and matched reference solutions within 1%. Software QA log archived in institutional repository."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Order-of-accuracy test demonstrates solver achieves nominal second-order spatial convergence on smooth manufactured solution.",
      "rationale": "Method of manufactured solutions (MMS) applied to the incompressible Navier-Stokes solver kernel. Observed order of accuracy p=1.94 on three systematically refined grids, consistent with the nominal second-order finite-volume scheme. Global L2 error norms for velocity components converge monotonically."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Grid convergence index (GCI) < 5% for NIH quantity of interest on medium grid relative to Richardson-extrapolated value.",
      "rationale": "Three grids (coarse 2.1M, medium 5.8M, fine 14.2M hexahedral cells) generated with systematic refinement ratio r=1.38. GCI computed per Celik et al. (2008) protocol. Medium-grid GCI for NIH at worst-case operating point (4 L/min, 3500 RPM) = 3.7%. Production runs executed on medium grid."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions (flow rate, rotational speed, fluid temperature, hematocrit) documented and matched to CFD boundary conditions within specified tolerances.",
      "rationale": "FDA interlaboratory study protocol specifies bovine blood at 37°C, hematocrit 30±2%, controlled flow rates via calibrated Coriolis meters (±0.5%). CFD boundary conditions set to nominal protocol values. Temperature deviation of ±1°C from nominal assessed as negligible for viscosity sensitivity. Test condition fidelity rated adequate for MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric (relative hemolysis index RH) computed for all five operating points; all RH < 1 and maximum absolute percent error < 20%.",
      "rationale": "RH computed as NIH_CFD / NIH_predicate for each operating point. All five values satisfy RH < 1. Maximum absolute percent error between CFD and experimental mean NIH is 14.3% at the 2 L/min, 2500 RPM condition. Inter-laboratory experimental variability (CV 18–23%) acknowledged in acceptance determination."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "NIH and RH are established regulatory QoIs for hemolysis assessment of blood-contacting devices; their relevance to the COU decision is documented.",
      "rationale": "NIH is the FDA-recognized scalar metric for pump-induced hemolysis per the ASTM F1841 standard. RH relative to a predicate device is the accepted comparative basis for 510(k) submissions for Class II CPB devices. QoI relevance to the COU decision (worst-case operating condition identification) is direct and well-established in the literature."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
